</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Appendiceal neoplasms are uncommon tumors of the gastrointestinal tract that may manifest with symptoms of appendicitis, right lower quadrant pain, or palpable mass, leading to imaging or surgical intervention. The majority of appendiceal masses consist of primary epithelial neoplasms and neuroendocrine tumors (NETs). Epithelial neoplasms—mucinous and nonmucinous types—are more often detected at imaging than NETs due to their larger size and propensity for peritoneal spread and metastatic disease. Epithelial mucinous neoplasms are defined by the presence of mucin, detected at radiologic and pathologic examination. A mucocele or pseudomyxoma peritonei from epithelial mucinous tumors are the two most common cross-sectional imaging findings of appendiceal mucinous neoplasms. Nonmucinous epithelial tumors are less common and manifest as masses similar to colonic-type malignancies. NETs are often discovered incidentally at appendectomy due to their small size and nonaggressive behavior. Imaging findings of primary appendiceal tumors may overlap with those of acute appendicitis. Additionally, an appendiceal mass may cause acute appendicitis, obscuring the underlying mass. Other neoplasms including lymphoma, sarcoma, mesenchymal and nerve sheath tumors, or secondary malignant involvement of the appendix are rare. Treatment depends on the histologic subtype and extent of disease. Detailed description of organ, nodal, and peritoneal involvement informs surgical management with the goal of complete cytoreduction. Novel treatments such as hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy have increased survival for patients with mucinous tumors.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160150">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160150">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig1.jpeg" height="1789" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. The appendix (arrowhead) originates from the appendiceal orifice, approximately 2 cm below the ileocecal valve. The mesoappendix (arrow) contains the appendicular artery. Lymphatic drainage occurs through the ileocolic nodes and venous drainage through the ileocolic veins (not shown). <i>TI</i> = terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig2a.jpeg" height="1350" width="1910" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Mucocele from <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 33-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a dilated thin-walled appendix (arrow) containing hyperintense fluid. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a long retrocecal appendix (arrows) filled with hyperintense fluid. Signal intensity varies based on the specific protein content of the fluid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig2b.jpeg" height="1350" width="1033" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Mucocele from <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 33-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a dilated thin-walled appendix (arrow) containing hyperintense fluid. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a long retrocecal appendix (arrows) filled with hyperintense fluid. Signal intensity varies based on the specific protein content of the fluid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig3.jpeg" height="844" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Gross specimen of a mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 72-year-old woman. The appendix is opened to demonstrate copious mucosa-associated, tenacious, gelatinous mucin <i>(M)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig4.jpeg" height="1693" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Mucocele from <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 41-year-old man. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a markedly distended appendix containing low-attenuation mucin <i>(M)</i> with a small focus of wall calcification (arrow). A diameter greater than 2 cm suggests a neoplastic cause. Perihepatic mucin is present (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig5.jpeg" height="963" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 64-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated fluid-filled appendix with wall thickening (black arrows) and surrounding inflammation (arrowheads). The appendiceal tip is less dilated (white arrow). This manifestation of appendiceal mucinous neoplasm may result from tumor infiltration or superimposed appendicitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig6.jpeg" height="1448" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Gross and sectioned specimen of a mucocele complicated by appendicitis in a 32-year-old man. The appendix is dilated and contains a mucocele at the appendiceal tip (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig7a.jpeg" height="1199" width="1965" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 62-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Transabdominal longitudinal (left) and transverse (right) US images show a blind-ending tubular structure with posterior acoustic enhancement in the right lower quadrant, without surrounding free fluid. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a distended thin-walled appendix filled with hyperintense fluid (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig7b.jpeg" height="1199" width="1385" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 62-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Transabdominal longitudinal (left) and transverse (right) US images show a blind-ending tubular structure with posterior acoustic enhancement in the right lower quadrant, without surrounding free fluid. <b>(b)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows a distended thin-walled appendix filled with hyperintense fluid (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig8a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1397" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images 12 months <b>(a)</b> and 22 months <b>(b, c)</b> after appendectomy show progressive accumulation of mucin in the pelvis (arrows). There is mass effect on the urinary bladder <i>(B)</i> and ureters (not shown), resulting in bilateral hydronephrosis. There is also perihepatic mucin (arrowhead in <b>c</b>). Note the fibroid uterus <i>(U)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig8b.jpeg" height="1680" width="1448" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images 12 months <b>(a)</b> and 22 months <b>(b, c)</b> after appendectomy show progressive accumulation of mucin in the pelvis (arrows). There is mass effect on the urinary bladder <i>(B)</i> and ureters (not shown), resulting in bilateral hydronephrosis. There is also perihepatic mucin (arrowhead in <b>c</b>). Note the fibroid uterus <i>(U)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig8c.jpeg" height="1680" width="1504" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images 12 months <b>(a)</b> and 22 months <b>(b, c)</b> after appendectomy show progressive accumulation of mucin in the pelvis (arrows). There is mass effect on the urinary bladder <i>(B)</i> and ureters (not shown), resulting in bilateral hydronephrosis. There is also perihepatic mucin (arrowhead in <b>c</b>). Note the fibroid uterus <i>(U)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig9.jpeg" height="1520" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 76-year-old man. Photograph of a gross specimen of the omentum shows innumerable mucinous nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig10.jpeg" height="1730" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 52-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows mucinous ascites in the paracolic gutters and subdiaphragmatic region, exerting mass effect on the liver and spleen, which demonstrate a scalloped appearance. Linear calcifications of the mucinous deposits are seen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig11.jpeg" height="1554" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 59-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows loculated peritoneal low-attenuation collections with mass effect and invasion of the abdominal wall and small-bowel loops (arrows). Curvilinear calcifications are present (arrowhead). The patient had undergone right hemicolectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig12a.jpeg" height="1079" width="1740" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled and hyperemic appendix, with mucinous deposits posterior to the appendix (arrow) and along the right paracolic gutter, and with peritoneal soft-tissue implants (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue implants along the omentum (arrowheads) and serosal implants on the liver capsule (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal US image shows a serosal implant on the liver capsule (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig12b.jpeg" height="1769" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled and hyperemic appendix, with mucinous deposits posterior to the appendix (arrow) and along the right paracolic gutter, and with peritoneal soft-tissue implants (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue implants along the omentum (arrowheads) and serosal implants on the liver capsule (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal US image shows a serosal implant on the liver capsule (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig12c.jpeg" height="1079" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a fluid-filled and hyperemic appendix, with mucinous deposits posterior to the appendix (arrow) and along the right paracolic gutter, and with peritoneal soft-tissue implants (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue implants along the omentum (arrowheads) and serosal implants on the liver capsule (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal US image shows a serosal implant on the liver capsule (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig13a.jpeg" height="1306" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows a dilated appendix (arrows) and low-attenuation ascites in the pelvis (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows a distended appendix (arrow) and multiple enhancing peritoneal implants (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig13b.jpeg" height="1306" width="1976" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. <abbr title="low-grade appendiceal mucinous neoplasm">LAMN</abbr> and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows a dilated appendix (arrows) and low-attenuation ascites in the pelvis (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows a distended appendix (arrow) and multiple enhancing peritoneal implants (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig14a.jpeg" height="1308" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> with signet ring cells in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a distended fluid-filled appendix (black arrow) and diffuse omental nodularity (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial <sup>18</sup>F-<abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr> PET image shows moderate uptake in the omental soft-tissue nodules (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the omentum shows multiple signet ring cells, characterized by intracellular accumulation of mucin (arrows), which compresses and displaces the nuclei to the periphery in a crescent-like shape (arrowheads). (Hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig14b.jpeg" height="1459" width="1897" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> with signet ring cells in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a distended fluid-filled appendix (black arrow) and diffuse omental nodularity (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial <sup>18</sup>F-<abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr> PET image shows moderate uptake in the omental soft-tissue nodules (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the omentum shows multiple signet ring cells, characterized by intracellular accumulation of mucin (arrows), which compresses and displaces the nuclei to the periphery in a crescent-like shape (arrowheads). (Hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig14c.jpeg" height="1459" width="1459" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix and <abbr title="pseudomyxoma peritonei">PMP</abbr> with signet ring cells in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a distended fluid-filled appendix (black arrow) and diffuse omental nodularity (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial <sup>18</sup>F-<abbr title="fluorodeoxyglucose">FDG</abbr> PET image shows moderate uptake in the omental soft-tissue nodules (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of the omentum shows multiple signet ring cells, characterized by intracellular accumulation of mucin (arrows), which compresses and displaces the nuclei to the periphery in a crescent-like shape (arrowheads). (Hematoxylin-eosin [<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr>] stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig15.jpeg" height="1374" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Well-differentiated mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a man with abdominal pain. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a dilated appendix containing low-attenuation fluid (black arrow), with asymmetric wall thickening and focal calcification. There is periappendiceal fat stranding with small discrete mucin deposits (white arrow) and irregular omental thickening (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig16a.jpeg" height="1217" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 47-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a distended appendix (arrows) that is replaced by a soft-tissue mass. Periappendiceal fat stranding and prominent ileocecal lymph nodes (arrowheads) are present. The tip of the appendix is less dilated and seen lateral to the tumor. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of adenocarcinoma arising in a low-grade mucinous neoplasm shows a mucin pool <i>(M)</i> lined by columnar glandular epithelium in an undulating and flattened pattern (arrows). The invasive tumor extends into the muscularis propria (arrowheads). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumor cells with crowded round to oval nuclei with prominent nucleoli and foamy cytoplasm (arrows). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig16b.jpeg" height="1774" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 47-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a distended appendix (arrows) that is replaced by a soft-tissue mass. Periappendiceal fat stranding and prominent ileocecal lymph nodes (arrowheads) are present. The tip of the appendix is less dilated and seen lateral to the tumor. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of adenocarcinoma arising in a low-grade mucinous neoplasm shows a mucin pool <i>(M)</i> lined by columnar glandular epithelium in an undulating and flattened pattern (arrows). The invasive tumor extends into the muscularis propria (arrowheads). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumor cells with crowded round to oval nuclei with prominent nucleoli and foamy cytoplasm (arrows). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig16c.jpeg" height="1774" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 47-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a distended appendix (arrows) that is replaced by a soft-tissue mass. Periappendiceal fat stranding and prominent ileocecal lymph nodes (arrowheads) are present. The tip of the appendix is less dilated and seen lateral to the tumor. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of adenocarcinoma arising in a low-grade mucinous neoplasm shows a mucin pool <i>(M)</i> lined by columnar glandular epithelium in an undulating and flattened pattern (arrows). The invasive tumor extends into the muscularis propria (arrowheads). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumor cells with crowded round to oval nuclei with prominent nucleoli and foamy cytoplasm (arrows). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig17.jpeg" height="1608" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Nonmucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix in a 61-year-old woman with right lower quadrant pain. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a heterogeneous mass in the right lower quadrant in the expected location of the appendix (arrows). Pathologic analysis revealed moderately to poorly differentiated adenocarcinoma, nonmucinous type.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig18.jpeg" height="1487" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Nonmucinous tubulovillous adenoma in a 72-year-old man. Coronal nonenhanced CT image shows dilatation and diffuse mural thickening of the appendix (arrows), with mild periappendiceal fat stranding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig19.jpeg" height="1672" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 15-year-old girl with acute appendicitis. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows an inflammatory mass with nodular enhancement (arrows) and surrounding fat stranding. The terminal ileum is seen (arrowheads). <i>C</i> = cecum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig20a.jpeg" height="1056" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 33-year-old woman with appendicitis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show appendiceal wall thickening, enhancement, and mural calcifications (arrows), with infiltration of the mesoappendiceal fat. There is dilatation of the appendiceal tip. Pathologic analysis revealed a 2.3-cm well-differentiated carcinoid with extension through the appendiceal wall into the mesoappendiceal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig20b.jpeg" height="1895" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 33-year-old woman with appendicitis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show appendiceal wall thickening, enhancement, and mural calcifications (arrows), with infiltration of the mesoappendiceal fat. There is dilatation of the appendiceal tip. Pathologic analysis revealed a 2.3-cm well-differentiated carcinoid with extension through the appendiceal wall into the mesoappendiceal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig21.jpeg" height="1465" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a patient with appendicitis. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a right lower quadrant mesenteric soft-tissue mass with irregular borders and desmoplastic reaction (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig22a.jpeg" height="1129" width="1799" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image during the arterial phase shows peripherally enhancing masses in the liver (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the classic carcinoid insular growth pattern (arrows), consisting of solid islands of uniform polygonal cells with retraction from the stroma. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig22b.jpeg" height="1550" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 46-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image during the arterial phase shows peripherally enhancing masses in the liver (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows the classic carcinoid insular growth pattern (arrows), consisting of solid islands of uniform polygonal cells with retraction from the stroma. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×100.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig23a.jpeg" height="1241" width="1705" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows an enhancing soft-tissue mass at the base of the cecum (arrow). There are dilated small-bowel loops due to extension of the tumor into the ileocecal valve, causing proximal obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Coronal <sup>111</sup>In octreotide image shows focal activity in the right lower quadrant (arrow), corresponding to the CT abnormality. Otherwise, there is normal biodistribution of the radiotracer without evidence of metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig23b.jpeg" height="1716" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image with intravenous and oral contrast material shows an enhancing soft-tissue mass at the base of the cecum (arrow). There are dilated small-bowel loops due to extension of the tumor into the ileocecal valve, causing proximal obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Coronal <sup>111</sup>In octreotide image shows focal activity in the right lower quadrant (arrow), corresponding to the CT abnormality. Otherwise, there is normal biodistribution of the radiotracer without evidence of metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig24.jpeg" height="1958" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 32-year-old man. Photograph of the sectioned specimen shows a carcinoid tumor (arrows) filling a distended appendiceal lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig25a.jpeg" height="1815" width="1535" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 19-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal US image of the right lower quadrant shows a noncompressible dilated appendix with irregular wall thickening and a hyperechoic nodule at its tip (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows carcinoid cells that form acini, trabeculae, and cords (arrows). The tumor cells show round to oval nuclei with a coarsely granular pattern (arrowhead). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig25b.jpeg" height="1815" width="1815" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. <abbr title="neuroendocrine tumor">NET</abbr> of the appendix in a 19-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Longitudinal US image of the right lower quadrant shows a noncompressible dilated appendix with irregular wall thickening and a hyperechoic nodule at its tip (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows carcinoid cells that form acini, trabeculae, and cords (arrows). The tumor cells show round to oval nuclei with a coarsely granular pattern (arrowhead). (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig26.jpeg" height="1151" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Burkitt lymphoma of the appendix in a 20-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a homogeneously enhancing soft-tissue mass in the expected location of the appendix.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig27a.jpeg" height="1184" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span>. High-grade B-cell lymphoma of the appendix in a 49-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a dilated appendix with homogeneous soft-tissue attenuation (arrow), with preserved vermiform appearance. There is marked mesenteric and retroperitoneal adenopathy (arrowheads), causing right hydronephrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig27b.jpeg" height="1616" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span>. High-grade B-cell lymphoma of the appendix in a 49-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a dilated appendix with homogeneous soft-tissue attenuation (arrow), with preserved vermiform appearance. There is marked mesenteric and retroperitoneal adenopathy (arrowheads), causing right hydronephrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig28a.jpeg" height="1086" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Breast cancer metastasis to the appendix in a 59-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse submucosal edema of the appendix (arrows) and cecal base (arrowhead) with hyperenhancement of the appendiceal mucosa and extensive surrounding soft-tissue infiltration. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows numerous small nests of pleomorphic tumor cells with irregular hyperchromatic nuclei (arrow) within the appendiceal wall. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig28b.jpeg" height="1750" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Breast cancer metastasis to the appendix in a 59-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse submucosal edema of the appendix (arrows) and cecal base (arrowhead) with hyperenhancement of the appendiceal mucosa and extensive surrounding soft-tissue infiltration. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows numerous small nests of pleomorphic tumor cells with irregular hyperchromatic nuclei (arrow) within the appendiceal wall. (<abbr title="hematoxylin-eosin">H-E</abbr> stain; original magnification, ×400.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160150/asset/images/large/rg.2017160150.fig29.jpeg" height="1632" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span>. Appendiceal involvement by high-grade serous ovarian carcinoma in a 58-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows direct spread of the right adnexal tumor (black arrow) to the adjacent appendix (white arrow), with tumor thrombus distending the contiguous gonadal vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160150&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Connor SJ, Hanna GB, Frizelle FA. Appendiceal tumors: retrospective clinicopathologic analysis of appendiceal tumors from 7,970 appendectomies. <em>Dis Colon Rectum</em> 1998;41(1):75–80.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02236899">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9510314/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Appendiceal+tumors%3A+retrospective+clinicopathologic+analysis+of+appendiceal+tumors+from+7%2C970+appendectomies&amp;author=SJ+Connor&amp;author=GB+Hanna&amp;author=FA+Frizelle&amp;publication_year=1998&amp;journal=Dis+Colon+Rectum&amp;pages=75-80&amp;doi=10.1007%2FBF02236899&amp;pmid=9510314">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Turaga KK, Pappas SG, Gamblin T. Importance of his